<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="542" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,718,1391]" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,718,743]" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">Description.</emphasis>
Fore wing length 
<quantity box="[505,653,718,743]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.55" metricValueMax="1.6" metricValueMin="1.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="542" unit="mm" value="15.5" valueMax="16.0" valueMin="15.0">15 to 16 mm</quantity>
. Ovipositor sheath length 
<quantity box="[949,1097,719,743]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.95" metricValueMax="3.1" metricValueMin="2.8" pageId="1" pageNumber="542" unit="mm" value="29.5" valueMax="31.0" valueMin="28.0">28 to 31 mm</quantity>
. Inner margins of eyes almost parallel. Clypeus evenly convex, median portion of apical margin distinctly elevated. Upper tooth of mandible slightly longer than lower tooth. Malar space 0.7 × as long as basal width of mandible. Occipital carina complete. Genal carina reach hypostomal carina above base of mandible. Epomia absent. Posterior portion of mesosternum with large sublateral tubercle. Posterior transverse carina of mesosternum absent. Metasternum in front of posterior coxae with strong sublateral longitudinal carina. Fore wing with vein 1cu-a distal of 1/M by 0.4 × as long as 1cu-a. Areolet oblique quadrangular, petiolate. Distance from vein 2rs-m to 2m-cu approximately 2.2 × as long as distance from 2m-cu to 3rs-m. Hind wing vein 1-cu about 1.5 × as long as cu-a. Claw pectinate (
<figureCitation box="[1335,1422,970,995]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="7.[151,250,977,999]" captionText="FIGURE 11. Verruca dentia Sheng &amp; Sun, sp. nov., holotype female. Hind claw." pageId="1" pageNumber="542">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
). Propodeum evenly convex, without carina except indistinct pleural carina. Propodeal spiracle elliptical. Metasoma elongate. First tergite 1.9 to 2.3 × as long as apical width, with glymma. Second tergite about as long as first tergite. Third tergite distinctly longer than apical width. Ovipositor sheath longer than body length, 4 to 5 × as long as hind tibia. Dorsal valve of ovipositor with deep subapical notch. Subapical portion of ventral valve of ovipositor with distinct vertical ridges (
<figureCitation box="[415,498,1150,1175]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="8.[151,250,422,444]" captionTargetBox="[352,1247,210,395]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[340,1247,193,400]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 14. Verruca dentia Sheng &amp; Sun, sp. nov., holotype female.Apical portion of ovipositor in lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1228003/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="542" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,718,1391]" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,326,1186,1211]" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">Etymology</emphasis>
. The name of the new genus is based on the large sublateral tubercle of mesosternum. The gender is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="542" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,718,1391]" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1258,1283]" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">Remarks</emphasis>
. This new genus can be easily distinguished from other genera of tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Seyrig" authorityYear="1932" box="[1130,1239,1258,1283]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Atrophini">Atrophini</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: Apical median portion of clypeus distinctly elevated. Posterior portion of mesosternum with large sublateral tubercle. Metasternum in front of posterior coxae with strong sublateral longitudinal carina. Subapical portion of ventral valve of ovipositor with distinct vertical teeth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1005,1438,1463]" box="[151,1005,1438,1463]" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">In Townes’s (1970) key to genera, the new genus can be inserted as follows:</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1510,1737]" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">
23. Nervellus weakly inclivous, vertical, or weakly reclivous. Tarsal claws short to long, usually pectinate. First tergite stout to slender, near base usually with some traces of longitudinal ridges.............................................. 23’ -. Nervellus strongly reclivous, intercepted far below the center. Tarsal claws long, pectinate. First tergite slender, mat, without longitudinal ridges, its punctures fine and weak. Mexico and Southwestern United States.............. 6. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Townes" authorityYear="1969" box="[1269,1373,1597,1619]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Loxodocus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1269,1373,1597,1619]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">Loxodocus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(P.27) 23’. Epipleurum of tergite 5 not separated by a crease. Posterior portion of mesosternum with large sublateral tubercle (
<figureCitation box="[1316,1372,1628,1649]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="4.[151,250,745,767]" captionTargetBox="[302,1284,193,724]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[302,1284,193,724]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 6. Verruca dentia Sheng &amp; Sun, sp. nov., holotype female.Mesosoma in lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1227989/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Apical portion of ventral valve of ovipositor with distinct teeth (
<figureCitation box="[804,875,1657,1678]" captionStart="FIGURE 14" captionStartId="8.[151,250,422,444]" captionTargetBox="[352,1247,210,395]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[340,1247,193,400]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 14. Verruca dentia Sheng &amp; Sun, sp. nov., holotype female.Apical portion of ovipositor in lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1228003/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). China.............. 
<taxonomicName authority="Sheng &amp; Sun" authorityName="Sheng &amp; Sun &amp; Wang &amp; Wu" authorityYear="2018" box="[1124,1336,1657,1678]" class="Maxillopoda" family="Verrucidae" genus="Verruca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sessilia" pageId="1" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1124,1200,1657,1678]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">Verruca</emphasis>
Sheng &amp; Sun
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1346,1435,1656,1678]" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">gen. nov.</emphasis>
-. Epipleurum of tergite 5 separated by a crease. Mesosternum without tubercle. Apical portion of ventral valve of ovipositor without teeth................................................................................ 5. 
<taxonomicName box="[1342,1435,1716,1737]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Lissonota" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1342,1435,1716,1737]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">Lissonota</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,1781,1842]" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">
It should be noted that two genera of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Seyrig" authorityYear="1932" box="[616,728,1781,1806]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Atrophini">Atrophini</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Townes 1978" authorityName="Townes" authorityYear="1978" box="[739,1007,1781,1806]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Helotorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[739,851,1781,1805]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">Helotorus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[858,1007,1782,1806]" pageId="1" pageNumber="542" refId="ref4011" refString="Townes, H. K. &amp; Townes, M. (1978) Ichneumon-flies of America north of Mexico: 7. Subfamily Banchinae, tribes Lissonotini and Banchini. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 26, 1 - 614." type="journal article">Townes 1978</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Ugalde &amp; Gauld 2002" authorityName="Ugalde &amp; Gauld" authorityYear="2002" box="[1062,1432,1781,1806]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Wahlamia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="542" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1062,1172,1781,1805]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="542">Wahlamia</emphasis>
Ugalde &amp; 
<bibRefCitation box="[1297,1432,1781,1806]" pageId="1" pageNumber="542" refId="ref3347" refString="Gauld, I. D., Sithole, R., Gomez, J. U. &amp; Godoy, C. (2002) The Ichneumonidae of Costa Rica. 4. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 66, 1 - 768." type="journal article">Gauld 2002</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, also have ovipositor with ridges. The new genus can be distinguished from them by the following key.
</paragraph>
